# Llama 3 8B on TPU v7x — prefill-heavy 1800 in / 128 out.
#
# Same shape as bm-infra's accuracy_jax.csv mmlu rows (1800/128, ratio
# ~14:1). The QC repo doesn't use this shape for v7x perf today, but
# it's the closest match they have to a prefill-dominated workload —
# which is where the chunk_prefill_size optimization should shine
# (more chunks per prompt → larger PREFILL bucket each step).
#
# All values use `: "${VAR:=default}"` so an env var set by the
# caller wins over the default here. That makes this case file
# reusable across sweeps that override individual axes.
#
# Two bash quirks worth knowing:
#   1. The colon-form `:=` triggers on unset OR empty, so passing
#      `VAR=""` from the caller silently picks up the default here.
#      To override, set a non-empty value.
#   2. The script (run_benchmark.sh) uses `VAR="${VAR:-default}"` for
#      its own defaults; the `:-` operator only substitutes, but the
#      outer `VAR=` does the assignment. End state is identical to the
#      `:=` form here. We use `:=` in case files because `set -a` then
#      auto-exports the side-effect; the script doesn't need that.

# Instruct variant rather than base. Identical attention shape (32
# q-heads / 8 kv-heads / head_dim=128 / no sliding window) so the v7x
# kernel tunes still apply. But the Instruct tokenizer config has
# `chat_template` set, which is needed to satisfy an unconditional
# assertion in vllm/benchmarks/datasets/datasets.py:get_samples that
# crashes on the base models missing template (the fallback
# `default_chat_template` was removed from a recent transformers and
# the LKG vllm bench code has not caught up). For throughput
# benchmarking on the sonnet completion dataset, base vs Instruct is
# a no-op for kernel work — the chat template just gates the
# bench-side assertion.
: "${MODEL:=meta-llama/Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct}"
: "${TENSOR_PARALLEL_SIZE:=1}"

: "${MAX_NUM_SEQS:=128}"
: "${MAX_NUM_BATCHED_TOKENS:=10275}"
: "${MAX_MODEL_LEN:=10275}"

# vLLM's --block-size (KV-cache page size). Empty = let vLLM pick its
# default for this version (the value drifts across releases — check
# the vllm CLI or its --block-size doc for what your install uses).
# Set to 64 or 128 to match a tuned page_size from the kernel-tuning
# table.
: "${BLOCK_SIZE:=}"

: "${DATASET:=sonnet}"
: "${INPUT_LEN:=1800}"
: "${OUTPUT_LEN:=128}"
: "${NUM_PROMPTS:=1000}"
